dc.name: dc
example: let test value => dc value >> out 0

sin.name: sin
example: let test f => sin f >> out 0

saw.name: saw
example: let test f => saw f >> out 0

tri.name: tri
example: let test f => tri f >> out 0

square.name: square
example: let test f => square f >> out 0

pulse.name: pulse
pulse.description: A pulse wave oscillator with variable duty cycle.
example: let test f w => pulse f w >> out 0

blip.name: blip
blip.description: An oscillator with a variable number of harmonics of equal amplitude.
example: let test f n => blip f n >> out 0

formant.name: formant
formant.description: Generates a set of harmonics around a formant frequency at a given fundamental frequency.

params.name: bwf
params.description: Pulse width frequency. Must be >= fundf.

example: let test fund form bwf => blip fund form bwf >> out 0

impulse.name: impulse
impulse.description: Generates single sample impulses at a frequency.
example: let test f => impulse f >> out 0

white.name: white
example: let test a => white a >> out 0

pink.name: pink
example: let test a => pink a >> out 0

brown.name: brown
example: let test a => brown a >> out 0

gray.name: gray
example: let test a => gray a >> out 0

clipNoise.name: clipNoise
clipNoise.description: Generates noise whose values are either -1 or 1.
example: let test a => clipNoise a >> out 0

crackle.name: crackle
crackle.description: A noise generator based on a chaotic function.

params.name: chaos
params.description: A parameter of the chaotic function with useful values from just below 1.0 to just above 2.0. Towards 2.0 the sound crackles.

example: let test c => crackle c >> out 0

dust.name: dust

params.name: density
params.description: Average number of impulses per second.

example: let test d => dust d >> out 0

noiseN.name: noiseN
example: let test f => noiseN f >> out 0

noiseL.name: noiseL
noiseL.description: A linearly interpolated random number generator
example: let test f => noiseL f >> out 0

noiseX.name: noiseX
noiseX.description: A cubic interpolated random number generator
example: let test f => noiseX f >> out 0

cuspN.name: cuspN
cuspN.description: A non-interpolating sound generator based on the difference equation: x[n+1] = a - b * sqrt(abs(x[n]))
example: let test f a b xi => cuspN f a b xi >> out 0

cuspL.name: cuspL
cuspL.description: A linearly interpolating sound generator based on the difference equation: x[n+1] = a - b * sqrt(abs(x[n]))
example: let test f a b xi => cuspL f a b xi >> out 0

gbmanN.name: gbmanN
gbmanN.description: A non-interpolating sound generator based on the difference equation: x[n+1] = 1 - y[n] + abs(x[n]); y[n+1] = x[n];
example: let test f xi yi => gbmanN f xi yi >> out 0

gbmanL.name: gbmanL
gbmanL.description: A linearly interpolating sound generator based on the difference equation: x[n+1] = 1 - y[n] + abs(x[n]); y[n+1] = x[n];
example: let test f xi yi => gbmanL f xi yi >> out 0

lowpass.name: lowpass
example: let test f q => white 1 >> lowpass f q >> out 0

highpass.name: highpass
example: let test f q => white 1 >> highpass f q >> out 0

bandpass.name: bandpass
example: let test f q => white 1 >> bandpass f q >> out 0

lag.name: lag
lag.description: Ramp a signal between two values over time.
example: let test lagtime => noiseN 100 >> lag lagtime >> out 0

crush.name: crush
example: let test b => sin 440 >> crush b >> out 0

decimate.name: decimate
decimate.description: Sample rate reduction on a signal.
example: let test r => sin 440 >> decimate r >> out 0

allpassN.name: allpassN
allpassN.description: An allpass delay line with no interpolation.

params.name: decay

example: let test del => impulse 1 >> allpassN del del 1 >> out 0

allpassL.name: allpassL

params.name: decay

combN.name: combN

combL.name: combL

params.name: decay
params.description: Time for the echoes to decay by 60 decibels.

example: let test del => impulse 1 >> combL del del 1 >> out 0

combC.name: combC

delayN.name: delayN
delayN.description: A simple delay with no interpolation.
example: let test del => impulse 1 >> delayN del del >> out 0

delayL.name: delayL

env.name: env
env.description: Envelope generator. Used for amplitude envelopes, will automatically free the synth when finished.

params.name: levels
params.description: The levels that the envelope will move through

params.name: times
params.description: The times it takes for the env to move between levels. Should be 1 item less than levels

params.name: shape
params.description: Either a shape number or string. Some examples: -4, 0, 1, "linear", "squared"

example: let test amp => white amp >> env [0,1,0] [1,1] "linear" >> out 0

env2.name: env2
env2.description: Envelope generator. Used for amplitude envelopes, will NOT automatically free the synth when finished.

params.name: levels
params.description: The levels that the envelope will move through

params.name: times
params.description: The times it takes for the env to move between levels. Should be 1 item less than levels

params.name: shape
params.description: Either a shape number or string. Some examples: -4, 0, 1, "linear", "squared"

perc.name: perc
perc.description: Envelope generator. Used for amplitude envelopes, will automatically free the synth when finished.

params.name: attackTime
params.description: Time for the envelope to go from 0 to the peak

params.name: peak
params.description: The highest level the envelope with reach

params.name: decayTime
params.description: Time for the envelope to go from the peak to 0

example: let test amp => white amp >> perc 0 1 1 >> out 0

perc2.name: perc2
perc2.description: Envelope generator. Used for amplitude envelopes, will NOT automatically free the synth when finished.

params.name: attackTime
params.description: Time for the envelope to go from 0 to the peak

params.name: peak
params.description: The highest level the envelope with reach

params.name: decayTime

out.name: out

params.description: The bus index to send to

example: let test bus => white 1 >> out bus

Takes `f` function and returns wrapper in return, that may be
used for tail recursive algorithms. Note that returned funciton
is not side effect free and should not be called from anywhere
else during tail recursion. In other words if
`var f = tco(function foo() { ... bar() ... })`, then `bar`
should never call `f`. It is ok though for `bar` to call `tco(foo)`
instead.

## Examples
var sum = tco(function(x, y) {
  return y > 0 ? sum(x + 1, y - 1) :
         y < 0 ? sum(x - 1, y + 1) :
         x
})
sum(20, 100000) // => 100020

Tag-closer extension for CodeMirror.

This extension adds an "autoCloseTags" option that can be set to
either true to get the default behavior, or an object to further
configure its behavior.

These are supported options:

`whenClosing` (default true)
  Whether to autoclose when the '/' of a closing tag is typed.
`whenOpening` (default true)
  Whether to autoclose the tag when the final '>' of an opening
  tag is typed.
`dontCloseTags` (default is empty tags for HTML, none for XML)
  An array of tag names that should not be autoclosed.
`indentTags` (default is block tags for HTML, none for XML)
  An array of tag names that should, when opened, cause a
  blank line to be added inside the tag, and the blank line and
  closing line to be indented.

See demos/closetag.html for a usage example.

Supported keybindings:

  Motion:
  h, j, k, l
  gj, gk
  e, E, w, W, b, B, ge, gE
  f<character>, F<character>, t<character>, T<character>
  $, ^, 0, -, +, _
  gg, G
  %
  '<character>, `<character>

  Operator:
  d, y, c
  dd, yy, cc
  g~, g~g~
  >, <, >>, <<

  Operator-Motion:
  x, X, D, Y, C, ~

  Action:
  a, i, s, A, I, S, o, O
  zz, z., z<CR>, zt, zb, z-
  J
  u, Ctrl-r
  m<character>
  r<character>

  Modes:
  ESC - leave insert mode, visual mode, and clear input state.
  Ctrl-[, Ctrl-c - same as ESC.

Registers: unamed, -, a-z, A-Z, 0-9
  (Does not respect the special case for number registers when delete
   operator is made with these commands: %, (, ),  , /, ?, n, N, {, } )
  TODO: Implement the remaining registers.
Marks: a-z, A-Z, and 0-9
  TODO: Implement the remaining special marks. They have more complex
      behavior.

 1. Default keymap
 2. Variable declarations and short basic helpers
 3. Instance (External API) implementation
 4. Internal state tracking objects (input state, counter) implementation
    and instanstiation
 5. Key handler (the main command dispatcher) implementation
 6. Motion, operator, and action implementations
 7. Helper functions for the key handler, motions, operators, and actions
 8. Set up Vim to work as a keymap for CodeMirror.

classitems.description:
Extract the regular expression from the query and return a Regexp object.
Returns null if the query is blank.
If ignoreCase is passed in, the Regexp object will have the 'i' flag set.
If smartCase is passed in, and the query contains upper case letters,
  then ignoreCase is overridden, and the 'i' flag will not be set.
If the query contains the /i in the flag part of the regular expression,
  then both ignoreCase and smartCase are ignored, and 'i' will be passed
  through to the Regex object.

Check if pos is in the specified range, INCLUSIVE.
Range can be specified with 1 or 2 arguments.
If the first range argument is an array, treat it as an array of line
numbers. Match pos against any of the lines.
If the first range argument is a number,
  if there is only 1 range argument, check if pos has the same line
      number
  if there are 2 range arguments, then check if pos is in between the two
      range arguments.

! Info
CoreVersion parameter is needed for TiddlyWiki only!

Helper to test CodeMirror highlighting modes. It pretty prints output of the
highlighter and can check against expected styles.

Mode tests are registered by calling test.mode(testName, mode,
tokens), where mode is a mode object as returned by
CodeMirror.getMode, and tokens is an array of lines that make up
the test.

These lines are strings, in which styled stretches of code are
enclosed in brackets `[]`, and prefixed by their style. For
example, `[keyword if]`. Brackets in the code itself must be
duplicated to prevent them from being interpreted as token
boundaries. For example `a[[i]]` for `a[i]`. If a token has
multiple styles, the styles must be separated by ampersands, for
example `[tag&error </hmtl>]`.

See the test.js files in the css, markdown, gfm, and stex mode
directories for examples.

Emulation of CodeMirror's internal highlight routine for testing. Multi-line
input is supported.

Extract the regular expression from the query and return a Regexp object.
Returns null if the query is blank.
If ignoreCase is passed in, the Regexp object will have the 'i' flag set.
If smartCase is passed in, and the query contains upper case letters,
  then ignoreCase is overridden, and the 'i' flag will not be set.
If the query contains the /i in the flag part of the regular expression,
  then both ignoreCase and smartCase are ignored, and 'i' will be passed
  through to the Regex object.

Helper to test CodeMirror highlighting modes. It pretty prints output of the
highlighter and can check against expected styles.

Mode tests are registered by calling test.mode(testName, mode,
tokens), where mode is a mode object as returned by
CodeMirror.getMode, and tokens is an array of lines that make up
the test.

These lines are strings, in which styled stretches of code are
enclosed in brackets `[]`, and prefixed by their style. For
example, `[keyword if]`. Brackets in the code itself must be
duplicated to prevent them from being interpreted as token
boundaries. For example `a[[i]]` for `a[i]`. If a token has
multiple styles, the styles must be separated by ampersands, for
example `[tag&error </hmtl>]`.

See the test.js files in the css, markdown, gfm, and stex mode
directories for examples.
